Setup — tools & environment
▼
Install tools
Node 20+Wrangler 3Vitest
Run npm install -D vitest wrangler @cloudflare/workers-types in your worker directory. Confirm node -v is ≥ 20 — the Web Crypto API used for SHA-512 requires it.
Create .dev.vars
Copy .dev.vars.example and fill with SISP test credentials. This file must never be committed. Values needed: POS_ID, POS_AUTH_CODE, SISP_URL, CALLBACK_SECRET. Wrangler reads this automatically on wrangler dev.
Caveat If .dev.vars is missing, the Worker boots but all fingerprint calls silently use undefined as the auth code — every hash will be wrong and you'll get SISP rejections with no obvious error message.
Add vitest.config.ts
environment: 'miniflare' gives you Web Crypto, TextEncoder, and crypto.subtle in tests without a real browser. Without this, crypto.subtle.digest is undefined and every fingerprint test throws TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined.

Phase 1 — fingerprint unit tests (offline, no SISP needed)
▼
Test 1a — sha512Base64 raw binary output
Vitest This is the single most important test. The SISP spec uses raw binary SHA-512 then base64 — not hex. If your implementation hashes to hex first, every downstream fingerprint is wrong.

Known input: "123456789A" → expected output: TrmzQzqPgdgicNXUMMKu8p+rtbSoqZDkXeHBZVeZdkyY/BhPZKArQpCJAP4GsPaJbviDg51P8iYlyohDjNr52w==

This value is printed verbatim in the Security Protocol PDF. If your function returns anything else, stop — the crypto is wrong before touching anything else.

Error to watch Getting a different base64 string that is 88 chars long but clearly different = you hashed to hex string then base64-encoded the hex. Use crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-512', encoded) and pass the raw ArrayBuffer to btoa, not the hex string.
Test 1b — send fingerprint (full field chain)
Vitest Use the worked example from the Security Protocol PDF section 2.4.1 with posAutCode="ttqRdOzmGvCSpuag". Verify your buildSendFingerprint produces the exact string shown.

Field order to verify: base64(sha512(posAutCode)) + timestamp + (amount×1000) + merchantRef.trim() + merchantSession.trim() + posID.trim() + currency.trim() + transactionCode.trim() then base64(sha512(concat)).

Caveat — amount scaling 500 CVE → 500000 not 500. CVE has no decimal places but the spec still multiplies by 1000. If you pass the integer 500 directly, the fingerprint is wrong. Use Math.trunc(amount * 1000).

Caveat — entityCode/referenceNumber These fields are only appended to the hash string when non-empty AND their leading zeros must be stripped: Number("00100") → 100. Test with and without them.
Test 1c — response fingerprint (success)
Vitest The PDF gives a full worked example for messageType=8. Expected result: URCdX5Y4D4YW1afIdlbdRMx+FDAt//jdvFJreGUZC98n2xepsGcAlgrWUPQj4n+lcWS04Dm9kNGY4G1N82pPeQ==

Caveat — clearingPeriod and transactionID The spec says strip leading zeros: "0000100" → "100". The PHP lib.php does NOT strip them explicitly — it passes raw values from $_POST. In the worked example SISP already sends "987" and "26" without leading zeros. Your Worker must handle both cases, stripping if needed.

Caveat — reloadCode This field keeps its zeros: "000000000000" stays as is. The PDF explicitly says do not strip this one. Test with empty string, zeros string, and a real code.
Test 1d — response fingerprint (error, messageType=6)
Vitest Error responses use a completely different field set. The PDF gives a worked example with messageType=6 and posAutCode="ttqRdOzmGvCSpuag". Expected: AYpWZLwKhnwXtfDAW4l15D9oM3fVtJOwZkKt89djbAZP+L2FW/hPuHeyMQQVmX16xvmoSzRptSNcM5AGy0Y93w==

Field order for error: base64(sha512(posAutCode)) + messageType + merchantRespMessageID + merchantRespErrorCode + merchantRespErrorDetail + merchantRespErrorDescription + merchantRespMerchantRef + merchantRespMerchantSession + merchantRespAdditionalErrorMessage + merchantRespTimeStamp

Common mistake Using the success field order for error responses. They share only the first field (hashed posAutCode). Everything else is different.
Run and confirm
npx vitest run --reporter=verbose

All four tests must pass before moving to Phase 2. Do not proceed if any fingerprint test fails — everything downstream depends on this being correct.

Test 2a — POST /create-payment returns correct fields
Vitest + Miniflare Send a valid JSON body with orderId, amount, merchantRef, callbackUrl, and minimal customer object. Assert the response contains: sessionId (UUID format), formHtml (contains a form tag with action pointing to SISP URL), and that fingerprint and TimeStamp appear in the URL query string — NOT only in the form body.

Caveat The original plugin appends FingerPrint, TimeStamp, FingerPrintVersion as query params on the action URL while also including them as hidden form fields. Replicate this exactly. Do not clean it up without confirming with SISP.
Test 2b — missing required fields returns 400
Vitest + Miniflare Send requests missing each required field one at a time: no orderId, no amount, no merchantRef, no callbackUrl. Each must return HTTP 400 with a JSON body containing error and field keys so the WordPress bridge knows which field is missing.

Caveat Do not return a plain string — WP's wp_remote_post will still get a 400 but won't be able to parse which field caused it. Return structured JSON errors from the start.
Test 2c — purchaseRequest JSON structure
Vitest Extract purchaseRequest from the generated form HTML, base64-decode it, parse the JSON. Verify all mandatory 3DS fields are present: email, billAddrCity, billAddrCountry (numeric, e.g. "132"), billAddrLine1, billAddrPostCode (never empty — use "0000" as fallback), acctInfo object with all six sub-fields.

Error to watch Country code sent as alpha-2 ("CV") instead of numeric ("132"). SISP will reject this silently — the payment page loads but the 3DS check fails.
Test 2d — POST /callback with valid fingerprint
Vitest + Miniflare Construct a fake SISP callback using the worked-example values from the Security Protocol PDF. Send as application/x-www-form-urlencoded. Assert: HTTP 200, session updated to success, WordPress notification queued via ctx.waitUntil (mock the fetch).

Also assert that merchantResp === "C" AND messageType === "8" are both checked — not just the fingerprint. A mismatched fingerprint that passes the type check should still fail.
Test 2e — /callback with tampered fingerprint
Vitest + Miniflare Send a callback where one field (e.g. merchantRespPurchaseAmount) has been changed after fingerprint generation. Assert: HTTP 200 still returned to SISP (always acknowledge), but session status set to failed and WordPress notified with status: "failed" and reason: "fingerprint_mismatch".

Caveat Always return 200 to SISP even on mismatch. If you return 400 or 500, SISP may retry the callback repeatedly, creating duplicate processing attempts.
Test 2f — amount mismatch
Vitest + Miniflare Create a session for 500 CVE. Send a callback where fingerprint is valid but merchantRespPurchaseAmount reports 600. Assert session is marked failed with reason amount_mismatch. This is how you catch SISP returning the right signature for the wrong amount — unlikely but in the spec.
