Phase 3 — end-to-end against SISP test environment
Get SISP test credentials
Email gestao.operacoes@sisp.cv and request: test POS ID, test POS AUTH CODE, test VBV URL, and test card numbers. They also provide a test environment URL. You cannot do Phase 3 without these — do not try to guess or reuse production credentials.

Important Test card numbers expire. If a test card worked last week and fails now, ask SISP for updated test cards before debugging your code.
Start wrangler dev with SISP test URL
wrangler dev Run wrangler dev --local. Wrangler exposes your Worker at http://localhost:8787. For SISP's callback to reach your local machine, you need a public tunnel. Use wrangler dev --remote (deploys to Cloudflare's edge, returns a temporary *.workers.dev URL) or a tunnel tool.

Error to watch wrangler dev --local will not receive SISP's callback POST because SISP cannot reach localhost. Use --remote for end-to-end tests, or set up a tunnel. The callback URL in your payment session must be the public-facing URL, not localhost.
Test 3a — full payment flow with test card
Browser + wrangler dev --remote Call POST /create-payment from a browser or curl. Paste the returned formHtml into a blank HTML page and open it — it should auto-submit and redirect to SISP's hosted card page. Enter the test card. After authentication, SISP should POST to your /callback.

Watch the wrangler dev console. You should see the callback request arrive. If it does not arrive within 30 seconds, SISP could not reach your callback URL — check that the URL in the form's urlMerchantResponse field is the public workers.dev URL, not localhost.

Error to watch — silent fingerprint failure If SISP's callback arrives but your Worker logs fingerprint_mismatch, print both the computed fingerprint and the received one to the console. Compare character by character. The most common causes: amount not multiplied by 1000, clearingPeriod not stripped of leading zeros, or reloadCode stripped when it should not be.
Test 3b — declined card flow
Browser + SISP test card for decline SISP provides specific test card numbers that trigger declines. Use one. Assert your /callback receives messageType=6, applies the error fingerprint formula (not the success formula), marks the session as failed, and passes the correct error fields to WordPress.

Common mistake Applying the success fingerprint formula to a messageType=6 response. They are different field sets. The error response fingerprint will always fail if you use the success formula — your code will flag every declined payment as a tampered response.
Test 3c — user cancels on SISP page
Browser Click cancel/back on the SISP hosted page. SISP will POST to your callback URL with userCancelled=true and NO messageType. Assert your Worker handles this branch: session set to failed, WordPress notified with status: "cancelled". Do not attempt fingerprint validation on a cancel callback — there is no fingerprint sent.
Test 3d — transaction status API (timeout simulation)
curl + SISP test env Create a payment session but do NOT complete the payment. After 60 seconds, call your GET /transaction-status?sessionId=.... The Worker should call SISP's /pos/transaction-status API with HTTP Basic auth (base64 of portalId:password — different credentials from POS auth code) and return the result.

Caveat The transaction status API uses different auth than payments. You need PORTAL_ID and PORTAL_PASSWORD as separate Worker secrets. If you reuse POS credentials here, SISP returns 401 with no explanation.
Phase 4 — WordPress bridge integration
▼
Test 4a — WP bridge calls /create-payment and embeds form
WP staging site + browser Activate the bridge plugin on a staging WooCommerce install. Place an order and reach the payment step. Assert: the bridge sends a POST to your Worker with integer CVE amount (not 25.00 — 2500 for 25 CVE), the Worker responds with formHtml, the bridge embeds and auto-submits the form, and the user lands on the SISP card page.

Caveat — WC amount format $order->get_total() in WooCommerce returns a string like "25.00". Your bridge must cast this to integer CVE before sending to the Worker. If you send 25.00 as-is, the Worker's fingerprint will scale it to 25000 not 25000 — wait, that's the same. But if it comes in as a float string "25.50" the scaling gives 25500 which is correct. The risk is when WC returns locale-formatted amounts like "1.250,00" on some European locales. Always do intval($order->get_total()) in the bridge.
Test 4b — WP receives payment result and updates order
WP staging + REST endpoint After a successful test payment (Phase 3a), verify that your WP REST endpoint /wp-json/morabeza/v1/payment-result receives the Worker's POST, validates the X-Secret header, finds the order by orderId, and transitions it to completed. Check the order notes in WP admin — they should include the SISP transaction reference.

Error to watch The WP endpoint must return HTTP 200 to the Worker even if the order update fails (e.g. order not found). If it returns 4xx/5xx, the Worker's ctx.waitUntil fetch fails silently — but more importantly, if you retry on failure you risk double-completing orders.
Test 4c — X-Secret header validation
curl POST to your WP REST endpoint without the X-Secret header, then with a wrong value. Both must return HTTP 403 and not update any order. This prevents anyone who discovers your callback URL from faking payment completions.

Then POST with the correct secret and a real order ID in a failed state. Assert the order moves to failed status.


Phase 5 — production smoke test
▼
Deploy and run a pilot transaction with SISP
wrangler deploy + SISP Per the migration FAQ (MD044), after integration you must do a pilot transaction in production with SISP present. Contact gestao.operacoes@sisp.cv to schedule this. They validate that your site sends the correct 3DS fields and that the callback fingerprint is verified correctly on your end.

Do not skip this step. SISP only enables international Visa/Mastercard processing after the pilot passes.
Run a real low-value transaction
Real card + production POS Use a real card for a 1 CVE or lowest-possible-amount transaction. Verify the order completes end-to-end in WooCommerce. Check D1 to confirm the session record shows status: success. Verify Cloudflare logs show the callback was received and processed without errors.
Monitor for 48 hours
Cloudflare Logs + D1 Watch for any fingerprint_mismatch errors — these should be zero on real traffic. Any occurrence means either your crypto implementation has an edge case or someone is tampering. Also watch for sessions stuck in pending — these mean callbacks are not arriving and the transaction-status recovery path needs testing.

